+Jerry VanNuys The thing about the concept of being a progressive, is that 
it does not bar you from carrying over certain traditionalist views. You 
have progressives who want full social and economic equality; but such 
progressives may say: "I believe in the 2nd amendment." The problem I see, 
is that many people I have spoken to ALWAYS associate someone with a left 
or right wing demographic; simply because that person has multiple opinions 
that aren't in the area that the person proclaims. 

Humans and their needs and desires can become a very complex area of study; 
and it has obviously been studied for many years. I think many people I get 
into debates with tend to forget how diverse and complicated we are as 
social beings. This creates grey areas between people which can in turn 
create misunderstandings. Is this intentional? Maybe. Progressive ideals 
that are applied into social mobility often create great solutions, but at 
the same time; they introduce new problems. Social equality for example; is 
a beautiful thing in its concept and application. The problem is; it gets 
twisted and corrupt by people who don't fully understand how equality 
works. 

How can it be a problem? In the case of Social Equality, it has more to do 
with people abusing the framework. People will go out and sue their boss; 
claiming the boss fired them because he was 'Racist'. People are more 
likely to believe that story than hold from the boss' perspective of that 
employee, being a incompetent worker who was insubordinate and harassed 
other people. Equality is a tool that gives leverage to people who want to 
act victimized to maintain their authority and status. That is a shame too, 
because the idea of equality just makes everyone have the same privilege; 
but in the work space; there are rankings and priorities. Some people are 
rejected a house, maybe because of bad credit. Does it make it ok for 
someone to use their race as an excuse for why they were denied a mortgage? 

So going back to gun rights; the people who want to abolish gun rights 
typically have good hearts; but they are also doing it on the wrong 
accounts. The common reasoning behind it is that some people are 
uncontrollable, some people are stupid intolerant rednecks, etc. Yes, you 
have these people; but what about people who need guns to keep themselves 
and their families safe? Anti-gun activists always like to argue that 
removal of guns can prevent future disaster. Can it? Sure, but the 
prevention of one disaster, allows another one to flourish. When it comes 
to equality, I think everyone has the equal right to defend themselves; and 
not everyone is a black belt martial artist or master fencer. 

Granted, using the second amendment as an excuse, could be viewed as 
maintaining authority and status. I am telling this because I myself am a 
progressive, but I also own 2 guns and I am very careful and responsible 
with them. Part of being someone who believes in equality, is someone who 
doesn't discriminate people who have certain wishes or advocacy; such as 
being entitled to own a gun. As a progressive gun owner, I think a license 
+ background check and a training certificate is definitely a good idea 
across the board; that could reduce gun-related accidents.

I think I want to point out that people make critique certain ideals and 
viewpoints; claiming flaws in them when in reality; every social and 
political ideal or belief is bound to be flawed. No matter how progressive 
you are, I think it is fair to point that humans are naturally 
materialistic hunter gatherers. There will never be an absolutely perfect 
and equal society; because everyone is different. I think privileges should 
be equal, but people themselves should take pride in their unique identity 
and beliefs. Equality in general wants to achieve this; but people who 
flash their status under it use it to make personal gains against others, 
instead of gains that don't take away from others.

I would like to thank Tex Grebner for originally posting the opening video 
of him.shooting himself in the leg. I remember when it first went up, many 
in the Right to Arms camp, especially trainers, condemned this guy for 
making us all look bad.

Not so. In any endeavor, people will make mistakes through carelessness, 
ignorance, and most especially, bad training. This happened because the 
shooter had, for an instant, allowed his finger to slip onto the trigger as 
he drew. My guess is that under most circumstances, he was not even aware 
he was doing that; his finger was probably laid against the barrel by the 
time he was in position to get a sight picture.  I wish somebody would put 
together a training video from this incident, going over the gun, the 
holster, the draw technique, and this video, frame by enhanced frame.

In one of the pilot magazines, there's a column titled "I Learned About 
Flying From That". I've seen similar columns in woodworking and carpentry 
magazines. The common feature is a discussion of something that went 
wrong--not to mock the erring individual, but to teach everyone something 
about their craft.

The aerospace folk in particular are obsessive about investigating 
accidents and less serious incidents and spreading the lessons learned far 
and wider. That's what the NTSB is for; not to fix blame, but to WORK THE 
PROBLEM.

If you shoot, watch this whole video. How soon, in each case, do you find 
yourself shouting "NO!" at the screen? In Grebner's case, it's not until 
his gun goes off; it takes careful study of each frame to understand 
exactly what went wrong. (If I remember correctly, his holster had 
something to do with it, too; its design was quite controversial even 
before this happened.)

In the second segment, with the rifle, the viewer should wince when the 
shooter pulls the trigger the second time after a misfire, then shriek in 
horror when he looks down the barrel. The proper procedure when a round 
doesn't fire is to keep the muzzle pointed in a safe direction, with your 
hand away from the chamber in case it blows up. (Details vary depending on 
the exact firearm involved, and every shooter should know and practice the 
no-fire drill for his weapon.)

The rest--bad stance, bad grip, too much gun for an inexperienced shooter, 
FAILURE TO SECURE A WEAPON IN THE PRESENCE OF A CURIOUS CHILD WHO HAS NOT 
BEEN WHUPPED FOR TOUCHING DADDY's GUN WITHOUT SUPERVISION.... on and on.

Bear in mind that incidents like these are extremely rare, given the number 
of gun owners out there, especially the number of new gun owners, and the 
toxic anti-training many of us received from movies and TV.

Gun ownership is on the rise here in the U.S., and thank Heaven and the 
Founders for that (and Barack Obama, gun salesman extraordinaire). For all 
the flack the "gun culture" gets, it actually serves a necessary purpose: 
to instill a proper respect for the tool involved, to develop good training 
techniques, and to spread tales of "I Learned About Shooting From That". As 
more and more people take up shooting, either for sport, self defense, or 
disaster prep, we are going to see more and more of this kind of thing. We 
all need to reach out to new shooters, kindly, tolerantly, patiently, 
remembering how ignorant we were our first time.﻿
